passages.text: In this week's Flyby, we provide context on TransDigm's special dividend vs. the dividend yield of S&P 500 sectors and individual companies in the S&P 500.

We have been fielding inbound questions from investors regarding how to think about TDG's recent special dividend announcement. We recognize that TransDigm's business has reached the size and scale in which it has been able to pay sizable special dividends to investors over the last few years in addition to completing accretive M&A deals. Given the success of TransDigm's business model and strong FCF generation (the company even generated positive FCF in the worst COVID- 19 quarter in June 2020), the company has created a repeatable and sustainable strategy to lever the balance sheet for acquisitions and special dividends and delevering through the normal course of business. TransDigm's most recent \(\sim\) 55bn ( \(\sim\) 90/share) special dividend announcement places its implied dividend yield at \(\sim 6.2\%\) , above that of all S&P 500 sectors and would make it the 11th highest dividend yield out of all companies in the S&P 500. We see the potential for TDG to continue to pay special dividends of this size or larger to reach its leverage target of 5x- 7x, absent a sizable M&A deal in the future. Below we provide additional details in charts. In our view, this ability for sizeable capital return is attractive. We maintain our Overweight rating as we continue to see positive risk reward for the stock.

We arrive at our PT of \(\) 1,750\(by using a 2026 EV/EBITDA multiple of\) \sim 24x \(and 2026E EBITDA of\) \sim \$ 5.2bn. A \(24x EV/EVITDA multiple is a\) \sim 3x- 4x\$ premium to today's NTM multiple of \(\sim 20 - 21x\) . We see a premium warranted given the strong demand backdrop for commercial aftermarket and TDG's strong pricing power given its large proportion of proprietary, sole source content.
